{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"haikuMasters","displayName":"Haiku Masters (Basho, Issa, Buson)","type":"quotes","language":"English","edition":"Public Domain Translations, Early 20th Century","primaryCategory":"Poetry & Literature","subcategory":"Haiku","audienceTags":["literature","mindfulness"],"sortPriority":55,"itemCount":50,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"browseOrder":"sequence","groupingLevels":["poet"],"groupingLabels":["Poet"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Haiku_Masters.json","version":"1.0"},"data":[{"id":"haiku-1","text":"An old silent pond. A frog jumps into the pond. Splash! Silence again.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":0},{"id":"haiku-2","text":"Over the wintry forest, winds howl in rage with no leaves to blow.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":1},{"id":"haiku-3","text":"In the cicada's cry there is no sign that can foretell how soon it must die.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":2},{"id":"haiku-4","text":"The sun path, hollyhocks turn toward it, through all the rains of May.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":3},{"id":"haiku-5","text":"Lighting one candle with another candle — spring evening.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":4},{"id":"haiku-6","text":"Even in Kyoto, hearing the cuckoo's cry, I long for Kyoto.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":5},{"id":"haiku-7","text":"A bee staggers out of the peony.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":6},{"id":"haiku-8","text":"From all these trees — in the salads, the soup, everywhere — cherry blossoms fall.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":7},{"id":"haiku-9","text":"Clouds appear and bring to men a chance to rest from looking at the moon.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":8},{"id":"haiku-10","text":"The moon and the flowers — forty-nine years — walking around, wasting time.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":9},{"id":"haiku-11","text":"The temple bell stops but I still hear the sound coming out of the flowers.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":10},{"id":"haiku-12","text":"Come, see real flowers of this painful world.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":11},{"id":"haiku-13","text":"Even a long journey begins with a single step.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":12},{"id":"haiku-14","text":"The first soft snow! Enough to bend the leaves of the jonquil low.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":13},{"id":"haiku-15","text":"On a withered branch, a crow has settled — autumn nightfall.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":14},{"id":"haiku-16","text":"The journey itself is my home.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":15},{"id":"haiku-17","text":"Autumn moonlight — a worm digs silently into the chestnut.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":16},{"id":"haiku-18","text":"What is there? Cherry blossoms in spring, cuckoo in summer, and in autumn the moon, and in winter the cold, clear snow.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":17},{"id":"haiku-19","text":"The winds that blow — ask them, which leaf on the tree will be next to go!","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":18},{"id":"haiku-20","text":"Don't weep, insects — even stars must say goodbye.","author":"Matsuo Basho","source":"Haiku by Matsuo Basho","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Matsuo Basho"},"sequenceIndex":19},{"id":"haiku-21","text":"Spring rain: conveyed to the rooftop by a slender rope.","author":"Yosa Buson","source":"Haiku by Yosa Buson","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Yosa Buson"},"sequenceIndex":20},{"id":"haiku-22","text":"Scattering cherry blossoms — moonlight faint in the dawn.","author":"Yosa Buson","source":"Haiku by Yosa Buson","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Yosa Buson"},"sequenceIndex":21},{"id":"haiku-23","text":"The spring sea all day long quietly heaving and falling.","author":"Yosa Buson","source":"Haiku by Yosa Buson","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Yosa Buson"},"sequenceIndex":22},{"id":"haiku-24","text":"White blossoms of the pear — a woman in moonlight reading a letter.","author":"Yosa Buson","source":"Haiku by Yosa Buson","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Yosa Buson"},"sequenceIndex":23},{"id":"haiku-25","text":"Short night — on the hairy caterpillar, beads of dew.","author":"Yosa Buson","source":"Haiku by Yosa Buson","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Yosa Buson"},"sequenceIndex":24},{"id":"haiku-26","text":"In the moonlight, the color and scent of the wisteria seems far away.","author":"Yosa Buson","source":"Haiku by Yosa Buson","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Yosa Buson"},"sequenceIndex":25},{"id":"haiku-27","text":"A village where they ring no bells — oh, what do they do at dusk in spring?","author":"Yosa Buson","source":"Haiku by Yosa Buson","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Yosa Buson"},"sequenceIndex":26},{"id":"haiku-28","text":"Tilling the field, the farmer is unaware of the skylark singing.","author":"Yosa Buson","source":"Haiku by Yosa Buson","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Yosa Buson"},"sequenceIndex":27},{"id":"haiku-29","text":"Sudden shower — grasping the grasses, two legs.","author":"Yosa Buson","source":"Haiku by Yosa Buson","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Yosa Buson"},"sequenceIndex":28},{"id":"haiku-30","text":"The short night is over, the waves washing the shore repeatedly.","author":"Yosa Buson","source":"Haiku by Yosa Buson","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Yosa Buson"},"sequenceIndex":29},{"id":"haiku-31","text":"This world of dew is only a world of dew — and yet, and yet.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":30},{"id":"haiku-32","text":"In this world we walk on the roof of hell, gazing at flowers.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":31},{"id":"haiku-33","text":"Don't worry, spiders — I keep house casually.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":32},{"id":"haiku-34","text":"O snail, climb Mount Fuji, but slowly, slowly!","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":33},{"id":"haiku-35","text":"Where there are humans, flies, and Buddhas.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":34},{"id":"haiku-36","text":"A world of dew — and within every dewdrop a world of struggle.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":35},{"id":"haiku-37","text":"Everything I touch with tenderness, alas, pricks like a bramble.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":36},{"id":"haiku-38","text":"The moon and the sun are passing travellers of a hundred generations.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":37},{"id":"haiku-39","text":"Under the mountain cherry tree, none are strangers.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":38},{"id":"haiku-40","text":"For you too, the nights must be long, lonely snail.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":39},{"id":"haiku-41","text":"Even this one firefly can fill the whole night with longing.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":40},{"id":"haiku-42","text":"Bright autumn moon — pond snails crying in the night.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":41},{"id":"haiku-43","text":"The snow is melting and the village is flooded with children.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":42},{"id":"haiku-44","text":"One human being, one fly, in a large room.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":43},{"id":"haiku-45","text":"Arising, the old man coughs. The sound of his cough — morning.","author":"Kobayashi Issa","source":"Haiku by Kobayashi Issa","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Kobayashi Issa"},"sequenceIndex":44},{"id":"haiku-46","text":"I want to sleep, swatting the flies as I doze.","author":"Masaoka Shiki","source":"Haiku by Masaoka Shiki","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Masaoka Shiki"},"sequenceIndex":45},{"id":"haiku-47","text":"In spring, cherry blossoms; in summer, the cuckoo; in autumn, the moon; in winter, cold and clear snow.","author":"Masaoka Shiki","source":"Haiku by Masaoka Shiki","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Masaoka Shiki"},"sequenceIndex":46},{"id":"haiku-48","text":"Tossing and turning in the night — how long the summer darkness!","author":"Masaoka Shiki","source":"Haiku by Masaoka Shiki","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Masaoka Shiki"},"sequenceIndex":47},{"id":"haiku-49","text":"The cuckoo — its voice fades away and only the moonlight remains.","author":"Masaoka Shiki","source":"Haiku by Masaoka Shiki","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Masaoka Shiki"},"sequenceIndex":48},{"id":"haiku-50","text":"Looking for the place where the mosquito went — all is quiet now.","author":"Masaoka Shiki","source":"Haiku by Masaoka Shiki","tags":["poetry","haiku","japanese","nature","language:english","collection:haiku"],"groups":{"poet":"Masaoka Shiki"},"sequenceIndex":49}]}